##Take-out riders, taxi drivers, couriers, volunteers... closed the city for nine days, they maintain the blood of Wuhan

Micro-signal GQREPORT

Function introduction, record the rise and fall of the characters and changes in the value of the Times. Complete, true, in-depth, accurate non-fiction stories, sent to you every week.

In a blink of an eye, the city of Wuhan has been closed for nine days. While most people are at home behind closed doors, some are still delivering supplies and supplies to the city, doing everything they can to keep the city running. If Wuhan today is compared to a human body that has been hit by a virus, they are like tiny, dense capillary, trying to carry on the city's bloodline.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
···············

❶

The delivery guy

Since the closure of the city, the entire Wuhan like the movie in the broadcast has been pressed the mute button. Most express delivery companies have almost stopped running, a large number of goods from outside the backlog in Wuhan's warehouse. A small number of Tmall Express, EMS, SF workers are still working, sometimes a courier to deliver two large areas, a mountain of goods from the warehouse at a slow rate of outward transportation.

On Jan. 26, Chang Cheh, a volunteer, called Wang, a delivery man he knew, and asked him to help retrieve from the warehouse a box of medical surgical masks he had sent from Cangzhou four days earlier. He promised to give you a bag of masks if you help me find this courier.

As soon as he got the mask, Chang Cheh rushed to the hospital. As an individual volunteer, Chang Cheh was able to find only a limited amount of supplies at a time. Between January 25 and 26, he found only 200 protective suits, 100 masks, and 100 goggles, er, fever clinic, he's got a little of each. Sometimes you can only get ten in one place, but whether you get ten cases or ten, the doctors are grateful. Every extra one is a lifesaver for the doctors.

Most of the shops on the formerly busy shopping streets have closed. In the supermarket, a lot of vegetables are gone. Cabbages and cabbages are much less available than they were a few days ago. Only one convenience store in the whole block of Xudong Street was still lit up. Door filled with convenient hot pot, instant noodles and other fast food. Many blue-helmeted take-out riders were waiting at the door to pick up their wares. Quite a number of people who dare not or can not go out, the acquisition of living materials rely entirely on shuttling riders in the city.

This is Wu Bang do take-away rider for the first time encountered by the customer to add wechat situation, the end of the first order, the customer carefully asked, can you add wechat? Every day or two after that, he would send a list of dishes and supplies, paying 20 yuan each time for running errands. Because his knees used to be bone fracture, Wu now walks with a limp and slowness. On January 28, Wu stayed at the Zhongbai Supermarket for two hours before he was able to buy what he needed. That night, when he went home to rest, Wu Bang "couldn't keep his eyes open. ".

During the siege, Wu Bang's running expenses did not change, a day down to earn more than usual. But different platforms have different policies. A young rider said his delivery fee had risen by at least 12 yuan around January 21, according to "spectator inSight" . He figured he could earn 3,000 to 5,000 yuan in three days. But most of the riders or dare not go out, and out of the riders to the hospital orders, but also rarely willing to take, "fear Ah. ".

Rider Liu gang sent abalone rice to Wuhan University Zhongnan Hospital on the First Day of the Lunar New Year. Arriving at the hospital, he got into the elevator, looked up and discovered that his destination, the 16th floor, was the respiratory department, which he was a little nervous about, but when he got up he found that it was much quieter than he had expected. The night before, Liu Gang saw a Weibo hot search, found that Wuhan Hospital dinner is to eat instant noodles, he blushed, decided to run the next day more hospital list. Some of the hospital orders were for him to take his mother's cooking to his father, a doctor who was on the front line saving lives.

Liu felt that the motivation to help others outweighed the fear of an epidemic among those still on the road after the city was closed. On Jan. 29, Liu gang photographed street sweepers in orange overalls, traffic police in fluorescent green vests under an overpass, cyclists in yellow uniforms eating on the side of the road, and pharmacies still open, "They're superheroes. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
And crosstown express is still running. Dada crowdsourced delivery man Li has been working around the clock in recent days. Of the nine deliverymen at his station, three had returned home for the Lunar New Year, leaving no one behind because of the outbreak. Three or four days when the city closed, a few local colleagues did not schedule at home to stay bored, and out to deliver express.

At present, Li Zaigui delivers in JD.com station, distributes some daily necessities: Mask, Rice, noodles, oil, instant noodles, mineral water. The platform specially instructs, when the courier delivers the goods, do not contact with the guest, lets them come down to take, or puts in the express cabinet.

Every day, Lee Jae Gui receives a mask from the platform, sometimes an N95, sometimes a medical mask. This is already a very good level in the industry. In fact, many of the people in the service sector, which supplies people with life and health care, have very poor protection of their own. Lin Chen, a short video blogger who has been out shooting in recent days, said that most of the riders he saw on the street were not wearing masks. Biker Wu Bang wears a mask and changes it daily, but he doesn't disinfect his clothes when he gets home, even though he often travels to the hospital to deliver food.

Some people lack access to and screening of information about the latest outbreak. On the fourth day of the siege, Chang Cheh, a volunteer, paid the driver an extra $10 to get into a taxi. When he got on the bus, he noticed that the driver was wearing only a scarf and no mask. He quickly gave her the mask he had in his bag. Seeing him so nervous, the driver asked, "Is it dangerous now? I heard that 200 people have been infected? "

A cloud of inadequate protection hung over everyone in the city. Every time Chang Cheh went to the hospital to deliver medical supplies, he and the doctors talked for a short time, separated by a certain distance, there's only one thing that keeps repeating itself over and over again: Forex, a promise that has been made to more than 30 doctors: "When you're ready, let's go out to dinner! " And no one dares to think about whether those promises, among Chang Cheh's doctor friends, will ever be fulfilled, a lot of people have been infected.

❷
Spontaneous Rescuer
"The medical staff themselves are struggling, and I want to help them with logistics as much as possible, " said Wang Hongyun, a volunteer at the hotel.
Since the beginning of Fengcheng, the support of the front-line medical staff logistics battle has started. On the second day of the New Year's Eve, when the city was closed down, seeing that many medical personnel were not provided with travel, food and accommodation, the hotel industry in Wuhan spontaneously organized the "Wuhan Medical Hotel Support Group" to free up their hotel rooms, free accommodation for medical staff.
At first, only twenty companies were involved, according to global travel. So far, support for the rescue has been Hongshan District, Wuchang District, Hankou and other 11 districts, a total of 316 hotels.
Wang Huan is one of the Group leaders and works as the hotel's "clinical examiner" . Over the past few days, she has felt a growing sense of loss in the hotel's rescue community. At the same time, the cost of rent, water and electricity continued to consume, disinfection and protection materials shortage, service manpower shortage. Businesses initially wanted to help some health care workers who were struggling to get home in the event of a traffic shutdown, but after a few days the transition was expected to be taken over by a government or charity.

Spontaneous Rescuer

At the same time, the cost of rent, water and electricity continued to consume, disinfection and protection materials shortage, service manpower shortage. Businesses initially wanted to help some health care workers who were struggling to get home in the event of a traffic shutdown, but after a few days the transition was expected to be taken over by a government or charity.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
One of the hotels offering hospital accommodation in the "Wuhan Hotel Rescue Group" photo: Spider Monkey bread

But now, the voluntary rescue of the people will obviously continue for a longer time. More and more paramedics are checking in. According to the Wuhan Medical Hotel Support Group table, 31 of the 61 hotels in Hankou are fully booked, and all the hotels adjacent to Union hospital are fully booked. In the early days of the rescue, however, many hotels did not even have disinfectant. Members of the rescue group voluntarily contact the community for donations, which will be distributed by the transportation of bottled water.

Wang Hongyun is the only remaining employee of the esky Boutique Hotel in Wuchang District. A lot of people quit years ago. Now, even with triple pay, they can't get jobs. He took on all the duties of receptionist, cleaner, store manager and so on. Over the past few days, Wang Hongyun did not sleep well, the phone kept ringing. The hotel has 30 rooms, 27 of which have been checked in, and people are calling to check in. Every day, he disinfects the public area with 84 disinfectant every three hours. This is the case for most hotels in Florida, where rooms are laid out and sheets are self-propelled by paramedics.

How disinfects, the protection appliance insufficiency has become these hotels to face the most severe question. Wang only wore a mask, no professional disinfection required isolation clothing, isolation shoes, no spray-type equipment, let alone ultraviolet lamp, air sterilizer. The paramedics who checked him in gave him two pairs of disposable gloves, which he still refuses to use.

How the front-line medical staff travel has also become one of the most concerned issues. "It's really not easy for our medical staff these days, " said Zhou Xianwang, mayor of Wuhan, in an interview with CCTV's face-to-face on January 27, the government tried, but failed, to provide a community with three to five taxis to take care of the community's medical staff.

At present, some medical staff have solved the problem of commuting by taking a rest near a hotel near the hospital. Some medical staff drive themselves to and from work. The remaining medical staff, is mainly through Didi Kuaiche Organization of a fast train volunteer team, as well as civilian volunteer fleet to solve the commuting problem.

Vlog blogger spider monkey bread on his way to the doctor's office in the morning

After the city was shut down, Wuhan's vlog blogger spider monkey bread joined the volunteer convoy, and he also recorded the interaction on the bus in a video format: After the doctor got off the bus, he took out a bottle of rubbing alcohol and sterilized the doctor's seat -- steps he learned from volunteers who helped others. When the first paramedic was picked up, he was given an N95 mask, which he said he bought online, while the doctor was wearing a surgical mask.

❸
The men who guard it
Fewer people traveled after the city was shut down. For Wuhan Police, the 110 alarm sounds are also less. On January 27, a public security bureau in Wuhan received a total of 165 cases of 110 police reports, down 67.8 percent from the daily average of 512 during that period.
"No one wants to talk about trivial matters anymore, " said Wang Xing, a Hankou police officer. In the past, police stations had to deal with a large proportion of petty fights a day, "On the shopping street, people who buy things say they want 70 yuan to buy them, and people who sell things say they want 80 yuan to sell them. When words don't match, they call the police. " Under the epidemic, there are fewer thieves. On the second day of the siege, the police at a police station in Hankou were at zero. Even accidental deaths are on the decline, and the almost daily number of road accidents that used to kill people in cities has disappeared.

The police are still on the job. The outbreak took a turn for the worse, with almost every community experiencing fever and no one daring to pick them up, with the police taking over. On January 30, he sent six suspected patients a day to a designated hospital and returned to the clinic, where he disinfected himself, his car and even his seat cushions with 84 and alcohol.
"For us, it's good to get the job done and we have no idea what to do tomorrow, " said Auxiliary Police Officer Yin Li. In the early morning of the 23rd, at the same time that Wuhan announced that the city would be closed, Yin Li's auxiliary police unit was temporarily ordered by the leadership to stop working. All colleagues who had taken a rest outside the city on that day were urgently recalled. On the day of the closure of the city, they helped passengers refund their tickets and maintained order at the bus and train stations in Wuhan. For Yin, his every workplace is dangerous, daughter-in-law pregnant, in case of their own infection to daughter-in-law how to do? Recently, Yin Lidu lived in a dormitory and was determined not to go home.
In the community, there are still many problems to be solved. A large number of chronic patients, elderly people are worried about the house, how to get medical treatment and buy food and supplies on time. The voluntary municipal taxi fleet currently provides part of the support for such situations. Taxi driver Yu Huahui is one of 6,000 taxi drivers who volunteered for the community project. (Note: The next day, the new pneumonia prevention and Control Headquarters in Wuhan issued notice No. 8.6,000 taxis were urgently collected from all over the city and allocated to the downtown area. Each community has 3-5 taxis, providing free services for residents in the area.)
Yu signed up at 8:40 a.m. and didn't learn of the subsidy until 9:00 p.m. He was joined in the call by half the drivers he knew. The night before the battle, Yu and his family had a "five-minute family meeting, " in which he said, "If I don't do this, I'll regret it for the rest of my life. " His wife and daughter eventually expressed their support, telling him to watch his back.
Every day, the community committee needs to use the car for the residents of the area to investigate the cause of travel, location, after screening, inform the driver. Before boarding, to check the temperature, the passengers who have fever can not get on the train.
A part of the vehicles to the hospital, with pregnant women physical examination, with dialysis patients to the hospital dialysis, with the elderly for physical examination. The other part is to help the elderly, who live inconveniently and have no children around, to solve the problem of purchasing goods. On a regular basis, the community worker keeps a list of the food and supplies they need and goes out with the driver to do the shopping. Sometimes Yu and his colleagues would have to visit several supermarkets and pharmacies to get all the items residents needed.
The taxi company supplied the drivers only with surgical masks and 84 disinfectant, and Yu added his own gloves, disposable raincoats, and plenty of traditional Chinese medicine to fumigate. Yu always felt the company had to do more to keep drivers safe. He tried to persuade his bosses that "I can provide as many N95 masks as the company needs" , "I have at least a few hundred, we can temporarily use. " But the leadership ignored him.

The Volunteer Fleet organized by ride-hailing Company Didi is more fully equipped, and the uniform yellow protective clothing in the news is dazzling. This makes master Hu "very sour. ". Net Source: Jingchu Net

Another driver, Hu, who volunteered to join the community, also felt the protection was inadequate, but did not speak to the company. "Now even the medical staff protection and other materials are poor, not here. " He sometimes feel aggrieved: "No one will pay attention to our area, we have no place to say, how to do? "

❹
To defend the city
Chang Cheh decided to take a break. As he worked as a volunteer at various hospitals delivering supplies, he thought he had developed symptoms of PTSD. Sometimes when he closes his eyes, thousands of hands are looking for a mask, and all he has is a bag.
Chang Cheh and his friends sent more than 1,000 protective suits and face masks from Fuyang. They drove to the entrance of the Wuhan Toll Station in the middle of the night. They could not get in. The road was cut off, things can not be thrown, and finally the goods had to drive back to the factory road.

Chang Cheh told no one that he was volunteering, that he was dealing with emotional problems, that he couldn't sleep all night, and that his personal strength was too limited.

Even more worrying for Chang Cheh is that a doctor friend of his at the People's hospital has been diagnosed with a strongly positive infection and is being quarantined. Strong infection means the virus in his system is more dangerous. The doctor, who was quarantined on Jan. 24 and initially had a low grade fever, continued to care for the most critical and infectious patients on his own every day until he was forced to stop working by medical staff. His Lung Shadow has spread to a large area. The doctor's family has not been informed of the situation. He is divorced and has no children.

Another of his doctor friends, who was exposed to the positive patients because he didn't have enough protection, had to be kept under observation because of the shortage of manpower, so he decided not to be satisfied with the isolation time and went back to work.

Chang Cheh never thought of herself as a volunteer. On New Year's Eve, while chatting with a doctor friend, the friend casually said that there was no food for them in the hospital on New Year's Eve, so Chang Cheh went to bring them food. On January 24th, at the height of the outbreak's panic, large numbers of people rushed to hospitals to be tested for infection. In the lobby of the hospital, Chang Cheh saw all middle aged and elderly people, some with their bodies pressed against their bodies, some without masks, some with cloth masks. Chang Cheh was about to make a detour when a pair of hands grabbed him, and a middle-aged woman with a scarf around her nose and mouth almost knelt down: "please sell me the mask. " Then another pair of hands grabbed him. Soon, Chang Cheh was out of masks.

Chang Cheh's heart was clenched with joy at the sight of the masks, and the hospital lobby was peppered with red faced patients. He felt that in such an environment, without proper protection, it would be difficult for others to escape the risk of infection. When the doctors saw him and asked him, he realized he was in tears. Before he left, the doctor advised him not to send anything after that. "It wasn't sick, but it was after that. " He nodded, turned around, and drove back to his friends on the road. "where can I get more protective materials? I'll buy some. "

"We are just the beginning of this kind of thing, but we can not solve the fundamental problem, " said Zhou Lei of the dejia instant hotel, whose hotel has joined the "Wuhan Medical Hotel Support Group. ".

"We also want to survive, " said Zhou Qinghui, owner of Yishang Garden Hotel. Her Hotel has 99 rooms, all air-conditioned (central air conditioning is not on) , and has hosted more than 50 health care workers over three nights. The cost of rent, water and electricity is about 6,500 yuan a day. In the early stage, Zhou Qinghui also purchased all the protective articles for the hotel. There were no protective clothing at the front desk, and she had purchased three "protective hooded raincoats" that she had heard could be reluctantly replaced.

"Our current conditions are not good enough for long-term free service, and how long we can last is uncertain, " Zhou said. The Wuhan Hotel Workers Wang Hongyun knew were having a hard time. "Most of the owners are not fully invested and a lot of them are opening shops and paying back loans, every month. "

In the early morning of January 29, "Wuhan 123 Rescue Team" in the fifth day of the establishment of a "sue driver friend letter, " announced that due to lack of protective resources such as protective clothing and masks, the immediate starting point, suspended orders. The five days, 123 rescue vehicles at risk of infection picked up nearly 1,000 medical personnel, transported more than 100 trips of supplies.

January 30th, "We defend Wuhan, please support us, " read a Weibo Post about a Wuhan Union Hospital who asked for help again! The Wuhan Union Hospital Again! We just got word that we're running out of supplies."Chang Cheh decided not to rest, he quickly packed up and went out, and set off again in search of supplies.
They continued to run, but also continue to wait, wait for the completion of the Fire Mountain and Thunder Mountain hospitals, waiting for the arrival of the inflection point of the epidemic, waiting for the lifting of the closure of the city, waiting for the time when the city re-energized.

Yu signed up at 8:40 a.m. and didn't learn of the subsidy until 9:00 p.m. He was joined in the call by half the drivers he knew. The night before the battle, Yu and his family had a "five-minute family meeting, " in which he said, "If I don't do this, I'll regret it for the rest of my life. " His wife and daughter eventually expressed their support, telling him to watch his back.
Every day, the community committee needs to use the car for the residents of the area to investigate the cause of travel, location, after screening, inform the driver. Before boarding, to check the temperature, the passengers who have fever can not get on the train.
A part of the vehicles to the hospital, with pregnant women physical examination, with dialysis patients to the hospital dialysis, with the elderly for physical examination. The other part is to help the elderly, who live inconveniently and have no children around, to solve the problem of purchasing goods. On a regular basis, the community worker keeps a list of the food and supplies they need and goes out with the driver to do the shopping. Sometimes Yu and his colleagues would have to visit several supermarkets and pharmacies to get all the items residents needed.
The taxi company supplied the drivers only with surgical masks and 84 disinfectant, and Yu added his own gloves, disposable raincoats, and plenty of traditional Chinese medicine to fumigate. Yu always felt the company had to do more to keep drivers safe. He tried to persuade his bosses that "I can provide as many N95 masks as the company needs" , "I have at least a few hundred, we can temporarily use. " But the leadership ignored him.

The police are still on the job. The outbreak took a turn for the worse, with almost every community experiencing fever and no one daring to pick them up, with the police taking over. On January 30, he sent six suspected patients a day to a designated hospital and returned to the clinic, where he disinfected himself, his car and even his seat cushions with 84 and alcohol.

"For us, it's good to get the job done and we have no idea what to do tomorrow, " said Auxiliary Police Officer Yin Li. In the early morning of the 23rd, at the same time that Wuhan announced that the city would be closed, Yin Li's auxiliary police unit was temporarily ordered by the leadership to stop working. All colleagues who had taken a rest outside the city on that day were urgently recalled. On the day of the closure of the city, they helped passengers refund their tickets and maintained order at the bus and train stations in Wuhan. For Yin, his every workplace is dangerous, daughter-in-law pregnant, in case of their own infection to daughter-in-law how to do? Recently, Yin Lidu lived in a dormitory and was determined not to go home.

In the community, there are still many problems to be solved. A large number of chronic patients, elderly people are worried about the house, how to get medical treatment and buy food and supplies on time. The voluntary municipal taxi fleet currently provides part of the support for such situations. Taxi driver Yu Huahui is one of 6,000 taxi drivers who volunteered for the community project. (Note: The next day, the new pneumonia prevention and Control Headquarters in Wuhan issued notice No. 8.6,000 taxis were urgently collected from all over the city and allocated to the downtown area. Each community has 3-5 taxis, providing free services for residents in the area.)

The Volunteer Fleet organized by ride-hailing Company Didi is more fully equipped, and the uniform yellow protective clothing in the news is dazzling. This makes master Hu "very sour. ". Net Source: Jingchu Net

Another driver, Hu, who volunteered to join the community, also felt the protection was inadequate, but did not speak to the company. "Now even the medical staff protection and other materials are poor, not here. " He sometimes feel aggrieved: "No one will pay attention to our area, we have no place to say, how to do? "

To defend the city
Chang Cheh decided to take a break. As he worked as a volunteer at various hospitals delivering supplies, he thought he had developed symptoms of PTSD. Sometimes when he closes his eyes, thousands of hands are looking for a mask, and all he has is a bag.
Chang Cheh and his friends sent more than 1,000 protective suits and face masks from Fuyang. They drove to the entrance of the Wuhan Toll Station in the middle of the night. They could not get in. The road was cut off, things can not be thrown, and finally the goods had to drive back to the factory road.

Chang Cheh told no one that he was volunteering, that he was dealing with emotional problems, that he couldn't sleep all night, and that his personal strength was too limited.

To defend the city

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Even more worrying for Chang Cheh is that a doctor friend of his at the People's hospital has been diagnosed with a strongly positive infection and is being quarantined. Strong infection means the virus in his system is more dangerous. The doctor, who was quarantined on Jan. 24 and initially had a low grade fever, continued to care for the most critical and infectious patients on his own every day until he was forced to stop working by medical staff. His Lung Shadow has spread to a large area. The doctor's family has not been informed of the situation. He is divorced and has no children.

Another of his doctor friends, who was exposed to the positive patients because he didn't have enough protection, had to be kept under observation because of the shortage of manpower, so he decided not to be satisfied with the isolation time and went back to work.

Chang Cheh never thought of herself as a volunteer. On New Year's Eve, while chatting with a doctor friend, the friend casually said that there was no food for them in the hospital on New Year's Eve, so Chang Cheh went to bring them food. On January 24th, at the height of the outbreak's panic, large numbers of people rushed to hospitals to be tested for infection. In the lobby of the hospital, Chang Cheh saw all middle aged and elderly people, some with their bodies pressed against their bodies, some without masks, some with cloth masks. Chang Cheh was about to make a detour when a pair of hands grabbed him, and a middle-aged woman with a scarf around her nose and mouth almost knelt down: "please sell me the mask. " Then another pair of hands grabbed him. Soon, Chang Cheh was out of masks.

Chang Cheh's heart was clenched with joy at the sight of the masks, and the hospital lobby was peppered with red faced patients. He felt that in such an environment, without proper protection, it would be difficult for others to escape the risk of infection. When the doctors saw him and asked him, he realized he was in tears. Before he left, the doctor advised him not to send anything after that. "It wasn't sick, but it was after that. " He nodded, turned around, and drove back to his friends on the road. "where can I get more protective materials? I'll buy some. "

"We are just the beginning of this kind of thing, but we can not solve the fundamental problem, " said Zhou Lei of the dejia instant hotel, whose hotel has joined the "Wuhan Medical Hotel Support Group. ".

"We also want to survive, " said Zhou Qinghui, owner of Yishang Garden Hotel. Her Hotel has 99 rooms, all air-conditioned (central air conditioning is not on) , and has hosted more than 50 health care workers over three nights. The cost of rent, water and electricity is about 6,500 yuan a day. In the early stage, Zhou Qinghui also purchased all the protective articles for the hotel. There were no protective clothing at the front desk, and she had purchased three "protective hooded raincoats" that she had heard could be reluctantly replaced.

"Our current conditions are not good enough for long-term free service, and how long we can last is uncertain, " Zhou said. The Wuhan Hotel Workers Wang Hongyun knew were having a hard time. "Most of the owners are not fully invested and a lot of them are opening shops and paying back loans, every month. "

In the early morning of January 29, "Wuhan 123 Rescue Team" in the fifth day of the establishment of a "sue driver friend letter, " announced that due to lack of protective resources such as protective clothing and masks, the immediate starting point, suspended orders. The five days, 123 rescue vehicles at risk of infection picked up nearly 1,000 medical personnel, transported more than 100 trips of supplies.

January 30th, "We defend Wuhan, please support us, " read a Weibo Post about a Wuhan Union Hospital who asked for help again! The Wuhan Union Hospital Again! We just got word that we're running out of supplies."Chang Cheh decided not to rest, he quickly packed up and went out, and set off again in search of supplies.
